\begin_layout Subsubsection
Internal Logical File
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ILFs, data created, stored and handled by the system, together with
 their complexity, are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
passenger data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi driver data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi call data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi reservation data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as
 simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
queue data: this is a complex data structure including data from several
 objects; we treat it as complex;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
zone data: a set of primitive data types, thus considered as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
request data: although this includes data from other objects, it has a really
 simple structure; thus, we treat it as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
notification data: this is just text to be sent to the user, thus we treat
 it as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
city topology data: this is the graph data structure mentioned in the DD;
 it is a big data structure retrieved from another source but still handled
 by the system; it is considered as complex;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By summing each weight for each ILF we find a total of 86 function points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
External Interface File
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EIFs, data used by the system but obtained from external sources, together
 with their complexity, are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GPS data from taxis: this is of course simple data;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
traffic data: this is used to update the city graph and it may contain a
 lot of information; thus we consider it as medium;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Google maps data (used by clients): this could be quite complex information
 but, considering our application does not manage it directly (it uses Google
 APIs), we consider it as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By summing each weight for each EIF we find a total of 17 function points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
External Input
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The External Inputs, elementary operations to process incoming data without
 producing any substantial output, together with their complexity are the
 following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
login (for passenger): this operation needs to perform only a few checks,
 thus we consider it simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
login (for drivers): there are just a few differences from the case above,
 thus we consider this as simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
registration: this must perform several operations (involving for example
 the validation via SMS), thus we consider it medium;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi call: this checks only a few things more than login, thus we still
 consider it simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
taxi reservation: it is very similar to a taxi call, thus we consider it
 simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
set busy: this is a trivial operation (removal of a driver from a queue),
 thus we consider it simple;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By summing each weight for each External Input we find a total of 19 function
 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
External Output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The External Outputs, elementary operations that generate data for the environme
nt, together with their complexity, are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
waiting time computation: this is a complex operation to be performed frequently
 (see DD, section 3.2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
queue position computation: this is a simple operation to compute the position
 of the driver in a queue;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
request computation: this is a simple operation to compute a request to
 be forwarded to a driver (it just puts together simple data);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
validation code computation: this is a simple operation to generate a random
 code;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By summing each weight for each External Output we find a total of 19 function
 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
External Inquiry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The External Inquiries, elementary operations involving input and output,
 together with their complexity, are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
receive notifications: this is a simple operation to retrieve the notifications
 of a certain user;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
set free: this is a simple operation to set a driver in free state (it also
 returns the queue position, that is why it is an external inquiry);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By summing each weight for each External Inquiry we find a total of 6 function
 points.
\end_layout

